Close

















Jane Martinson, media business editor







@janemartinson




Friday 4 February 2005 20.47 EST


First published on Friday 4 February 2005 20.47 EST







Lucian Grainge is sitting crosslegged on his office sofa, twiddling his fingers and trying not to sound irritated by questions about the role of big business in the music industry. The head of Universal Music UK - which sells one in four of the records we buy and manages acts from Keane to Eminem to U2 - is adamant that Universal is not really very commercial at all.
"What makes something corporate? I believe our company is the least corporate company in the corporate world," he says. "It's built up with a bunch of talented, focused, intelligent, passionate people who like developing music and making it. Why is that corporate?" 
It is a question that could be answered this Wednesday night at the annual industry love-in that is the British Record Industry Awards, or Brits. Millions of viewers will tune in to watch stars such as Franz Ferdinand, Joss Stone, Snow Patrol and both Bedingfields perform at the 25th anniversary event. Many more millions of pounds will be raised for charity, largely through corporate tables that dominate the space at the Earls Court event, rather than the few hundred screaming fans likely to dominate television screens. At last year's event, one industry executive described Beyoncé as a "great product, beautifully packaged". 
Grainge, 44 and a co-chairman of this year's event, has little time for those who fear the impact of the increasingly huge global record companies on the business. The awards are "an opportunity for us to enjoy and celebrate British music and celebrate the music business", he says. 
To be fair, Grainge and the British music industry itself have something to celebrate this year. The industry finds itself in positive sales territory for the first time in years, with a 3% increase in album sales. Universal's sales rose 12% in the UK last year, as the market leader managed to increase its share of the albums and singles market to more than 29%. It had three albums in the top 10, including the top two by Scissor Sisters and Keane. 
These two acts are also indicative of what has been described as a resurgent British music industry. (Scissors, an American band, were signed in the UK.) Four of the top five albums were by British acts last year, four of whom were previously unknown acts.
Peter Jamieson, chairman of the trade body, the British Phonographic Industry, says he can't remember the last time the charts were not dominated by foreigners. 
The success last year earned Grainge and his team a special mention in last week's results from its giant parent company, Vivendi Universal. They were praised for "an exceptional year for breaking new artists". 
It isn't long in the conversation with Grainge before talk turns to which new acts could help make this year as good as last. Any discomfort disappears and, like an ageing rock star coming into a packed auditorium, he jumps up from the sofa and runs over to his stereo system, shouting: "That's the best bit!" Before we know where we are he has turned up the volume on a demo disc and launched into a story about the Next Big Thing. 
The story starts when someone who knew Grainge 20 years ago rang and said he'd found a new talent. "He brings this guy in and I flip," says Grainge. "I do it on the spot. I call the head of Mercury [one of Universal's record labels] and I say, 'if you like this as much as I like it, we've got a deal'. 
'That's the gift' 
"This guy, Bobby Kray his name is, K-R-AY, he looks like someone from Jamiroquai yet has the voice of an angel. He was a choir boy at St Paul's or somewhere when he was 14 or something ... He's...," the machine-gun patter stalls momentarily, "He's stunning." 
But how can he tell that this new act will sell? Grainge, who is wearing a dark suit over an open-necked shirt revealing a mat of dark chest hair, leans over and says: "I can smell it. After 26 or 27 years, it's a smell." By this point, he is rifling through the stack of discs and tapes on his desk. We sit listening to at least five different, yet-to-be launched acts. 
Grainge, a stocky man, hums, nods and stamps along to the entire show. He knows the pauses, speaks up at the bits that need a little bit more work and points out the choruses that will work. 
How does this middle-aged man who grew up in north London loving the Clash and the Sex Pistols know what it takes for a hip-hop, pop or soul song to work? At this question, he smiles and says softly: "That's the gift." 
"I was a publisher for the first 10 years of my career. I understand songs. It's very, very difficult to define. I can definitely smell it. I can feel it in my fingertips." 
His ability to pick artists who work across a range of styles does mark Grainge out. But then it also marks out Universal, which produced half of the classical albums released last year, as well as Busted. 
His gift is allied to his business skills. In describing the first time he heard one new act, The Bravery, he says: "It was the best thing I'd heard. I absolutely loved it. It ticked every box - radio, TV, press, merchandise, the look, the trend." 
Yet it is impossible not to feel that Grainge really does love music and not just because the words "I love this business" and "I absolutely love this" act like a refrain to his speech.
He left school at 18 after walking out of an A-level exam to attend a meeting in which he helped to negotiate his first record deal. He earned £400 and knew he had "crossed a divide". "I felt comfortable and normal around musicians and artists and managers. I liked the social scene and loved the music. I was absolutely obsessed with it." 
His life today - regular dinners with Sir Elton John and a big house near Richmond, south-west London - is a far cry from his early days when his father owned a television and radio shop with "a carousel of 78s" in it and the young Lucian managed a band at school. 
Yet he maintains a link to what people really want, he says, by taking some of his senior managers to local high streets. "You're going to think I'm mad but what I do with my senior people is go and observe people," he says. 
"I love going to Coventry, Harrow, West Bromwich. That's where I walk into stores and get a sense of what people are wearing and what they want. There's an awful lot of data in the record business ... but to actually see these people and get a sense of demographics..." He tails off.
He is scathing of critics of reality-TV programmes such as Pop Idol or Fame Academy, describing them simply as "family entertainment". He adds: "Why not let people enjoy themselves? Why must we judge people all the time?" 
His first proper job was plugging songs, trying to get radio stations to play his company's music. Within five years he had moved to a record label and was director of A&R - artist and repertoire - which combines spotting talent with developing it. 
Grainge believes his background and that of his top team differentiates Universal from its main competitors, which are now reduced to three after Sony and BMG agreed to merge last year. Explaining the difference, Grainge says: "I am from an A&R background. All those other guys are from marketing." 
Jamieson at the BPI, who is co-chair of the Brits, says Grainge is a "one-off " in what can appear a cut-throat music business. "He can be both harsh and gentle, both businessman and music devotee." 
His boss, Doug Morris, chairman of Universal Music Group, has said of him: "He is so deceptive with that little kind face and those little glasses. Behind them, he is actually a killer shark." 
Despite his obvious love of the industry, Grainge is reluctant to name the music he listens to for pleasure. He begins by saying he can't listen to music at home as his youngest children, who are five and 11, overtake the system. So what does he listen to in the car alone? "I love listening to the Scissors in the car. They had the number-one biggest, most successful selling album last year." 
How about music he wasn't necessarily involved in? "The buzz of listening to one of the artists we have been involved with and which has sold millions is very therapeutic," he smiles. 
But is there any music he just really loves? Finally, he says: "Presley, Led Zeppelin, the Clash, the Sex Pistols." But he admits he could never name a truly favourite band, especially not a still-performing one, for fear of the people who would feel slighted. 
"When you're in this business, and particularly when you've been in this business since you were 18 like I have, there's no difference between the personal and business," he says.
Previous interviews have made much of the running machine, unplugged and unloved at the back of Grainge's office. But he seems to use up plenty of energy bouncing around the room and talking about work. "I love it. I am stimulated by it. The only time that the phone doesn't ring and the BlackBerry doesn't work is over Christmas. But that's because no one else is working." 
This Wednesday, Grainge is likely to be in his element. His front-row table at the Brits will be graced by some of Universal's top international executives, as well as the singer Amy Winehouse. 
A million miles away from all those record buyers in the Midlands. Yet when he hears that my mum is an Il Divo fan, he insists that I take her a new tape from a yet-to-be released crooner Patrizio Buanne. "She's a big market, your mum. Give her this and tell me what she thinks. Tell me as soon as possible. Before next week. Really, I mean it." And I think he really does.
The CV
 Born North London,1960 
 Education Left school at 18 
 Career
 1979 Joined April Music/CBS as a song plugger. Promoted to head of the creative department  1982 Director of RCA Music Publishing  1984 Director of A&R at MCA Records  1986 Set up PolyGram Music Publishing  1993  Joined Polydor as general manager of A&R and business affairs  1997 Promoted to managing director  2001 Promoted to deputy chairman of Universal Music UK  2001 Promoted to chairman and chief executive Director of the British Phonographic Industry and co-chairman of the Brits committee 
 Family Married with three children. Keen Arsenal fan


